# ============================================================
# NEGATIVE: Email and URL @ must NOT highlight as mention
# ============================================================

Email foo@bar.com — the @ here is part of an email, not a mention.
Send to alice@example.com please.
git@github.com:user/repo.git is an SSH URL.
user@host:~/path is a shell prompt fragment.
"quoted@string" should not mention.
prefix@notmention (no whitespace before @ = not a mention)


# ============================================================
# NEGATIVE: ? in URLs must NOT trigger question highlight
# ============================================================

https://example.com/path?q=1
https://example.com/search?query=hello&page=2
https://api.example.com/v1/users?id=42&format=json
The URL https://x.com/?ref=abc inside prose.


# ============================================================
# NEGATIVE: Inline parentheticals stay plain
# ============================================================

Meeting notes mid-line (with a parenthetical) that should stay plain text.
The token (here) and (here) and (here) should all be default color.
Multiple (one) (two) (three) parens in one line.
Nested ((double parens)) handling — grammar's call.
Compare to bracket-LINE labels which DO get colored (see positive section above).

Same rule for [inline brackets] and {inline braces} mid-line.
Code reference: see function([arg1, arg2]) for details.
Object: pass {key: value} as the second argument.


# ============================================================
# NEGATIVE: Markers mid-line do NOT trigger
# ============================================================

This sentence has a # in the middle and should not highlight.
The price is 5 + 3 = 8 (math, not markers).
Use - for hyphenation when needed.
She asked: "what about the * symbol?"
The < and > comparison operators in code: a < b > c.
Greater than > or less than < should not become refs mid-line.
Question? In the middle of a sentence. Not a question marker.


# ============================================================
# NEGATIVE: --dash patterns that are not flags
# ============================================================

em-dash—not-a-flag (em dash character is not two ascii dashes)
hyphen-word-with-dashes is normal text
prefix --middle-flag suffix (only the --middle-flag is a flag)
"--quoted-flag" inside a string — grammar's call whether to highlight
-text (single dash, no space — undefined per spec; should render plain)
---text (triple dash, no space — undefined per spec; should render plain)


# ============================================================
# NEGATIVE: Numbered/lettered patterns that aren't lists
# ============================================================

The version is 1.2.3 — not a list item.
He scored 9.5 on the test (decimal, not a list).
Section 2.1.4 of the spec (also not a list).
"1. first" inside a quoted string.
Item 1 of 3 — phrase, not a list marker.
e.g. is an abbreviation, not a lettered list.
i.e. same — needs whitespace handling.


# ============================================================
# NEGATIVE: Strings that aren't strings
# ============================================================

It's a contraction, don't highlight the apostrophe as a string.
"unclosed string at end of line
unclosed string with " in the middle but no closing quote
'single' quotes should render plain (single removed from spec)
`backtick` should also render plain (backtick removed from spec)
Mixed: "double works" 'single doesnt' `backtick doesnt` here.


# ============================================================
# NEGATIVE: Things that look like key:value but aren't
# ============================================================

The time is 10:30 and we should leave.
Ratio of 3:1 in favor.
URL fragment example.com:8080/path
"quoted: thing" inside a string.
Two colons:: should not highlight.
Indented but no value:
    just a dangling colon above
::starting with colon


# ============================================================
# NEGATIVE: Markers in code blocks (if grammar supports them)
# ============================================================

```
# this is inside a fenced code block
- so is this
@ and this
```

Grammar decision: do code fences suspend braindump tokens?
This file assumes YES — markers inside ``` should render plain.


